1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:26,320
Sorry everybody, my apologies.

2
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:34,960
That is a surprise. Michael's almost never late. And he hasn't worked here in four weeks.

3
00:00:34,960 --> 00:00:38,160
Hey, what are you doing?

4
00:00:38,160 --> 00:00:41,200
Overslept. Do you think anybody noticed I was late?

5
00:00:41,200 --> 00:00:42,760
I think they're just surprised you're here at all.

6
00:00:42,760 --> 00:00:44,720
Huh, that's him.

7
00:00:44,720 --> 00:00:47,200
Michael.

8
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:55,480
Gentlemen.

9
00:00:55,480 --> 00:01:06,080
Was I supposed to stop him? He seemed so confident.

10
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:08,080
No, they're good.

11
00:01:08,080 --> 00:01:20,080
Sorry. Sorry, sorry, sorry. Where's Ryan?

12
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:22,080
He's late.

13
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:55,880
It's 4.30 in the morning. Do you know where your kids are?

14
00:01:55,880 --> 00:01:59,880
If you are Ryan's parents or Pam's parents or my parents, you do.

15
00:01:59,880 --> 00:02:11,880
They're gonna be in this van with me. Who am I? Nothing to fear. I am just a 44-year-old guy with a paper route.

16
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:18,480
Time to make the donuts.

17
00:02:18,480 --> 00:02:20,080
Come on.

18
00:02:20,080 --> 00:02:21,680
Whoa!

19
00:02:21,680 --> 00:02:29,080
No, I promise I won't do it again. Come on.

20
00:02:29,080 --> 00:02:33,680
I lied!

21
00:02:33,680 --> 00:02:38,080
We've been making 5M deliveries for a couple weeks now.

22
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:50,880
Ever since I've gotten clean, there's something about fresh morning air that just really makes me sick.

23
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:54,680
Hello? Time to make the donuts.

24
00:02:54,680 --> 00:03:04,680
Oh, Halbert. Wow! Butter Patrol. Arrest that man. Your donuts make me go nuts.

25
00:03:04,680 --> 00:03:06,080
Hey, Pam.

26
00:03:06,080 --> 00:03:13,280
We got the van at a used car lot. We think it says, Hallelujah Church of Scranton in Korean.

27
00:03:13,280 --> 00:03:17,680
It was either this or an old school bus with an owl living in it.

28
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:20,480
You didn't happen to bring any coffee, did you, Michael?

29
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:21,680
Milk and sugar.

30
00:03:21,680 --> 00:03:27,480
Oh, awesome. You're a lifesaver.

31
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:29,880
Wait, is this just milk and sugar?

32
00:03:29,880 --> 00:03:30,880
That's what I said.

33
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:33,280
Do you drink this every day?

34
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:36,280
Every morning.

35
00:03:36,280 --> 00:03:41,680
We're doing okay. A couple weeks in, and we're having fun.

36
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:44,680
I consider myself someone who likes to work with his hands.

37
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:50,880
I type and I file and I will use a telephone.

38
00:03:50,880 --> 00:03:59,480
But I have found that one of the things I really enjoy about making my own deliveries is the ability to work with my feet as well.

39
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:05,480
I get to use the accelerator and the brake of the van.

40
00:04:05,480 --> 00:04:10,280
And I walk from the van.

41
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:13,280
And I walk back to the van.

42
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:19,480
So even though I consider myself a hands-on guy, I guess I'm also kind of a foots on guy.

43
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:21,880
20 of those.

44
00:04:21,880 --> 00:04:30,880
Oh, excuse me. Sorry. Sorry. No, it's a paper company now.

45
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:35,080
It's not for the church.

46
00:04:35,080 --> 00:04:39,480
Damn it! Where is my Amy room?

47
00:04:39,480 --> 00:04:41,680
What's wrong?

48
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:47,280
Two things. Can't find my Andy mug and I lost another client to the Michael Scott paper company.

49
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:49,280
Tell me about it. I lost two this week.

50
00:04:49,280 --> 00:04:54,280
I'm sorry. I thought it was a cute mug. You're making a funny expression.

51
00:04:54,280 --> 00:04:57,080
Ah.

52
00:04:57,080 --> 00:05:03,080
Then I decree that you, Lady Erin of Reception, enjoy the Andy mug.

53
00:05:03,080 --> 00:05:06,680
I'm really just mad about losing a client.

54
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:11,080
I heard that Michael is hand delivering the paper himself. And Ryan's a blonde now.

55
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:14,480
I heard they get sausage.

56
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:17,280
Sorry. This is really bothering me.

57
00:05:17,280 --> 00:05:21,480
Oh.

58
00:05:21,480 --> 00:05:23,680
This is yours, isn't it?

59
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:26,680
Okay. Who covers Van's pet grooming?

60
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:27,680
Oh, they're my client.

61
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:32,280
No. They were your client. They just called and said they're switching over to Michael Scott paper company.

62
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:35,480
Ah. Shame, Jim. I expected more.

63
00:05:35,480 --> 00:05:39,680
In the last month, we have lost ten major clients to Michael Scott.

64
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:42,080
What are we supposed to do? They keep undercutting us on price.

65
00:05:42,080 --> 00:05:46,080
I don't want to hear excuses. I want to see improvements. This is unacceptable.

66
00:05:46,080 --> 00:05:52,280
Hey, boss. I'd just like to point out that I have been here less time than these guys.

67
00:05:52,280 --> 00:05:55,880
Why are you telling me this?

68
00:05:55,880 --> 00:05:58,480
I just think the bar should be lower for a newbie.

69
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:03,680
Is this something you really want to have said?

70
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:07,280
I don't want to have said that.

71
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:10,480
But I think it's important that you know it.

72
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:14,880
I don't know what to do to inspire these people. Okay? Maybe it's my fault.

73
00:06:14,880 --> 00:06:18,280
It's not your fault. Some people just don't want to be inspired.

74
00:06:18,280 --> 00:06:25,080
I wrote a memo to all departments asking them to find ways to save money. But, uh...

75
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:28,080
Charles, I got your memo. Thank you.

76
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:31,280
I want you to know I'm putting my foot down when it comes to expense reports.

77
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:33,880
Waste not, want not.

78
00:06:33,880 --> 00:06:36,480
Well said, Angela.

79
00:06:40,480 --> 00:06:43,480
Been there, done that.

80
00:06:45,080 --> 00:06:48,280
Stanley?

81
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:49,880
Andrew?

82
00:06:49,880 --> 00:06:51,880
Rejected?

83
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:55,080
You never had a problem with me expensing cigars before.

84
00:06:55,080 --> 00:06:58,480
Yes, I did. I just didn't have the power to enforce it.

85
00:06:58,480 --> 00:07:01,880
Phyllis, this client you take out to offer it to us every Saturday night?

86
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:04,480
It wouldn't happen to be a refrigeration company, would it?

87
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:07,480
Michael never cared. He said it was a perk of the job.

88
00:07:07,480 --> 00:07:11,480
Hmm. I'm sorry. I get no joy from this.

89
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:14,480
Hey.

90
00:07:14,480 --> 00:07:15,880
Oh!

91
00:07:15,880 --> 00:07:18,080
You know what we need? We need some couches in here.

92
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:21,080
Michael, we should really consider getting a delivery guy.

93
00:07:21,080 --> 00:07:23,080
Oh. You know what you would love?

94
00:07:23,080 --> 00:07:25,480
Is if we built a loft.

95
00:07:25,480 --> 00:07:27,880
Why would I love that?

96
00:07:27,880 --> 00:07:29,280
Can we afford a delivery guy?

97
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:31,480
You can't afford a loft in a dorm room.

98
00:07:31,480 --> 00:07:35,280
You put your desk underneath, you have your loft up top, you can sleep up top.

99
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:36,880
Yeah, I know what a loft is.

100
00:07:36,880 --> 00:07:38,680
Most dorm rooms don't even have that.

101
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:40,080
Most do in the magazines.

102
00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:43,080
Let's see what a delivery guy costs.

103
00:07:44,480 --> 00:07:47,480
We should look into that.

104
00:07:47,480 --> 00:07:50,480
Or we just go for the loft.

105
00:07:53,280 --> 00:07:56,080
Would you let Charles know that David is here?

106
00:07:56,080 --> 00:07:57,480
Please.

107
00:07:57,480 --> 00:07:58,680
David. David Wallace.

108
00:07:58,680 --> 00:08:01,080
Hello, we've been expecting you, David Wallace.

109
00:08:01,080 --> 00:08:02,280
Charles and I were waiting for you.

110
00:08:02,280 --> 00:08:05,680
There he is. There he is. How was the trip up?

111
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:07,880
A lot better than a month at this Grand Radisson, I'm sure.

112
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:10,080
Oh, you know what? Hasn't been that bad.

113
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:12,880
Hasn't been that bad, these people who assaulted you up down here.

114
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:16,080
You couldn't ask for a better way to learn a company.

115
00:08:16,080 --> 00:08:18,480
I feel like I should be thanking you.

116
00:08:18,480 --> 00:08:20,480
Oh.

117
00:08:20,480 --> 00:08:22,480
The conference room is ready if we want to get started.

118
00:08:22,480 --> 00:08:24,680
You know, I just want to address everyone first.

119
00:08:24,680 --> 00:08:27,280
Oh, yeah, take your time. Stanley, pay attention.

120
00:08:27,280 --> 00:08:28,280
Hi, everyone.

121
00:08:28,280 --> 00:08:29,680
Hi.

122
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:30,680
Hi.

123
00:08:30,680 --> 00:08:32,280
Uh, look, it's no secret...

124
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:33,680
Hi.

125
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:34,880
Hello?

126
00:08:34,880 --> 00:08:38,080
Uh, it is no secret that Michael Scott Paper

127
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:40,680
has siphoned off a large chunk of our core business, and I'm here.

128
00:08:40,680 --> 00:08:45,280
I just want to reassure everyone that we think this is a good time to get started.

129
00:08:45,280 --> 00:08:46,880
I'm not going to let you down.

130
00:08:47,080 --> 00:08:51,480
I just want to reassure everyone that we think this is a temporary setback.

131
00:08:51,480 --> 00:08:52,480
Right.

132
00:08:52,480 --> 00:08:54,080
Okay?

133
00:08:54,080 --> 00:08:56,480
Maybe, and I don't know, if you'd just returned Michael's call,

134
00:08:56,480 --> 00:08:58,480
none of us would have lost clients.

135
00:08:58,480 --> 00:09:00,280
I've been wondering that myself lately.

136
00:09:00,280 --> 00:09:02,680
We're just going to get started, we're going to figure this out.

137
00:09:02,680 --> 00:09:05,480
Rest assured, Jim, can you come in with us, please?

138
00:09:05,480 --> 00:09:06,880
Oh, Jim, hold on.

139
00:09:06,880 --> 00:09:08,480
You know, David, uh, Dwight's been my guy.

140
00:09:08,480 --> 00:09:09,680
Yeah.

141
00:09:09,680 --> 00:09:10,680
Jim...

142
00:09:10,680 --> 00:09:13,280
Really? I find that extraordinarily surprising.

143
00:09:13,280 --> 00:09:15,080
Oh, he shows promise.

144
00:09:15,080 --> 00:09:17,680
And Jim, I don't know. I know he's been a disappointment.

145
00:09:17,680 --> 00:09:18,680
We'll bring them both.

146
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:19,680
Okay, great.

147
00:09:19,680 --> 00:09:20,680
Dwight, come on in.

148
00:09:20,680 --> 00:09:21,680
Also, Jim.

149
00:09:23,680 --> 00:09:25,680
Come along, afterthought.

150
00:09:27,680 --> 00:09:29,680
Well, this is very exciting.
